se.softhouse.jargo

Interface StringParser<T>

  • Type Parameters:
    T - the type to parse Strings into
    All Superinterfaces:
    Function<String,T>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    ForwardingStringParser, ForwardingStringParser.SimpleForwardingStringParser

    @Immutable
public interface StringParser<T>
extends Function<String,T>
    Parses Strings into values of the type T. Create an Argument for your StringParser with Arguments.withParser(StringParser). An example implementation for handling joda-time dates: 
     
 public class DateTimeParser implements StringParser<DateTime>
 {
        public static DefaultArgumentBuilder<DateTime> dateArgument(String ... names)
        {
                return Arguments.withParser(new DateTimeParser()).defaultValueDescription("Current time").names(names);
        }

        public String descriptionOfValidValues()
        {
                return "an ISO8601 date, such as 2011-02-28";
        }

        public DateTime parse(String value, Locale locale) throws ArgumentException
        {
                try
                {
                        return DateTime.parse(value);
                }
                catch(IllegalArgumentException wrongDateFormat)
                {
                        throw ArgumentExceptions.withMessage(wrongDateFormat.getLocalizedMessage());
                }
        }

        public DateTime defaultValue()
        {
                return DateTime.now();
        }

        public String metaDescription()
        {
                return "<date>";
        }
 }
 
 
     When printed in usage, this would look like:
 
 --start <date> <date>: an ISO8601 date, such as 2011-02-28
                Default: Current time
    Btw, this parser can be found in jargo-addons.
    See Also:
    StringParsers
